We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Submit RCIs to include only those released and cancelled, in compliance with the NGAS Manual. Alternatively, and to comply with GAM for LGUs when already in force, to have all checks prepared but shall be supported with a List of Unreleased Checks;

Prepare the Check Register in conformity with the format and instructions provided by the NGAS Manual;




Attach cancelled checks in the RCI. In this regard, the Municipal Treasurer is to submit cancelled checks to support its List of Cancelled/Spoiled Checks; and


Submit a List of Unreleased Checks as of December 31, 2021 and December 31, 2022.

Municipal Accountant to:

Record only those checks already issued and supported with DVs and supporting documents;




Submit the unsubmitted DVs and their supporting documents;




Prepare a journal entry to recognize and adjust the correct Cash in Bank balance and recognized liability accounts for the unreleased checks as of December 31, 2021, and December 31, 2022;




Report the cancelled checks as “cancelled” in the journals and submit them to the audit team as an attachment to RCIs.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that relevant information is supplied and available to the intended users of the Financial Statements, enabling them to make well-informed decisions based on a comprehensive understanding of the financial reports, henceforth:

include in the NFS disclosures on Biological Assets in compliance with IPSAS 27;



provide necessary disclosure of intangible assets in accordance with IPSAS 31;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Discontinuing the computation of depreciation expense reckoned from the voucher or check date of final and progress billing payments;

Request all subject documents of other PPAs not considered in this Observation and review the recognitions made in the books to determine whether the herein noted lapses and errors or mistakes are also applicable to these other PPAs or to other items of PPE already recorded in the book. Thereafter, prepare a working paper or summary of such;

Identify the depreciable components of the 14 PPAs which are classified as Road Networks pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008 and establish the proper and correct date of completion of 1 PPA which has material inconsistency on the date of completion as recommended in Observation No. 10;

After complying with Nos. 4 and 5, submit proofs, working papers, and summaries of the compliances to the audit team for verification in order to make and recognize the appropriate adjusting entry/ies; and

Make the appropriate adjustments to the affected Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Instruct the BAC to conduct a comprehensive and meticulous review of the guidelines on the use of FA before its implementation, with the primary objective of optimizing its potential to streamline the procurement process, promote efficiency, and guarantee transparency and accountability in government procurement; 

Direct the BAC to judiciously and meticulously accomplish the PBD template in agreement with the project requirements of each of the procurements at hand;

Instruct concerned offices to strengthen the internal control measures in the procurement requests or orders for contracts under the FA by integrating the guidelines outlined in the relevant sections of the NGAS Manual for LGUs and Appendix 32 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 to ensure the legality, validity, and propriety of procurements;

Require Requesting Office(s) to:

secure the Obligation Request before initiating procurement to ensure the availability of funds to cover the proposed expenditure;

promptly submit a duly accomplished original copy of Attendance Sheets, along with other aforementioned supporting documents, immediately after the activity took place, as these documents are expected to be completed and provided without delay following the closing of the activities;

submit a justification reporting addressing the inconsistencies found in the attached Attendance Sheets, and process the refund or submit a justification on what transpired regarding the double use of Attendance Sheets, resulting in double payment; and

strictly observe prudence on the use of government funds for the procurement of meals and snacks, ensuring that these are utilized only for expenses that are both regular and necessary;

Instruct the Inspection Committee to conduct the inspection and acceptance of delivered goods on the actual date of delivery to establish a reliable record of the supplier's fulfillment of its obligations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare letters addressed to claimants confirming the existence and accuracy of the balance of claims, and require their documents to support their claims; Certifies the reversion of funds to the General Fund after the establishment of the non-existence of claims;

Submit documents of the claims recognized under the Accounts Payable account for CY 2022 totalling ₱6,452,951.03. Otherwise, provide adjustment entry for its derecognition;



Submit documents of MOA of PPAs for implementation under Due to NGAs and Due to LGUs; and



Transfer specific purpose funds from General Fund to Trust Fund Books.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare utilization reports regularly, which shall be communicated and utilized for monitoring liabilities.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

Municipal Accountant to devise utilization reports the same way the specific PPAs are presented in the LDRRMF Plan;

LDRRM Officer, LDRRMC, Municipal Accountant, and other concerned officers are to include in their regular meeting the review of utilization reports;

LDRRM Officer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in identifying PPAs under Continuing Appropriations for its immediate implementation. In case of discontinuance, the PPAs shall be re-appropriated for their use; 

LDRRM Officer to include PPAs to be funded under the Special Trust Fund in the preparation of LDRRMFIP;


The Municipal Budget Officer to include the administrative expenses of the LDRRM Office under the General Fund instead of LDRRMF; and

Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the LDRRMO and MDPC to prioritize the implementation of LDRRMF because this attends to the basic needs of constituents within the community.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

BAC and TWG to:

Conduct strict, extensive and comprehensive post-qualification by scrupulously scrutinizing the documents submitted by the bidder particularly the Statement;

Require explanations from the contractors with regard to the inconsistencies noted between their bidding documents and eligibility requirements from the records of the Municipality;

Refrain from awarding contracts to contractors who are consistently not faithfully executing their obligations in accordance with their contracts.


Municipal Engineer and PMC, Chairperson to furnish the BAC and the TWG with pertinent relevant information which may aid them in conducting strict and comprehensive post-qualification.

We have recommended that the Management strictly follow the procedures on the disposal of government as prescribed under COA Circular 89-286 through the following:

Conduct inventory of unserviceable properties and create disposal and appraisal committee;




Submit the required documents prior to the disposal or divestment of assets; and


Request for COA-TAS for the inspection of the assets before demolition proper be done;


We have further recommended that the LCE:

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the approved documents for demolition including the duly approved IIRUP to the Municipal Accountant to serve as a basis to drop the previous asset accounts;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Drop from the books the demolished previous asset based on the Inspection and Inventory Report of Unserviceable Property; and 


Record the value of materials salvaged from the demolished old plaza, if any.

We have recommended that the LCE:

Judiciously and rigorously plan, budget, and evaluate the proposed procurement of parcels of land under the 20% DF in order to avoid the occurrence of the foregoing circumstances, such as conducting a feasibility study, legal and technical consultations to ensure the viability of the intended infrastructure projects in the future;

Scrupulously monitor the procured parcels of land and ensure that the intended infrastructure projects fall under the allowable projects listed under existing DILG-DBM JMCs;

Comply and submit the lacking required documentary requirements; and



Strictly adhere to the stipulations promulgated in every SB Resolution, and if so warranted, obtain prior authorization of the Sanggunian before acting on behalf of the Municipality especially on fiscal matters involving the utilization of funds.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the:

1.	Various department heads/requesting office to:

Judiciously plan and ascertain the anticipated events to be conducted in the ensuing calendar year and consider such in the inclusion of the procurement of meals and snacks in their preparation of PPMPs;


Prepare complete and properly filled-out PPMPs as useful basis of BAC for consolidation of APP;


Initiate the preparation of the Purchase Request and OBr within a reasonable time in order to instigate the whole procurement activity before the scheduled events.

Bids and Awards Committee to:

a. 	Consolidate PPMP and properly fill out the prescribed format of APP considering the requirements provided by the end user or requesting office as basis in initiating procurement activity;
b. (If small value procurement is employed) Institute controls, such as establishing ample interval days between the date of Purchase Request and OBr and the date of event, in order to ensure efficient and effective procurement activity.

In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended that the LCE direct the: 

Office of the Municipal Engineer to fast track the processing of the required documents on the completed infrastructure projects to facilitate payments thereof;



BAC Chairman to:

monitor each procurement activities specified in the Annual Procurement Plan and reflect the information in the Procurement Monitoring Report as well as the timeline on all procurement activities;

prepare, consolidate and submit the required Revised Annual Procurement Plan and Procurement Monitoring Report within the prescribed submission in the GPPB Circular not only to the Department of the Interior and Local Government for the purposes of compliance report for the Seal of Good Local Governance but on the obligations of the agency on the full disclosure and sustainability of transparent practice on how the public funds are managed, disbursed and used.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the:  

a)  Chairman of the BAC to immediately submit the required bidding documents which were not yet transmitted to the Audit Team and a written explanation why these were not submitted within 15 days from receipt hereof;  

b) BAC Secretariat to submit the correct document that would provide the exact contract duration of the project;  



c)  The Municipal Engineer to instruct the Contractor to revise the Statement of Work Accomplished using the proper/correct format showing details of item of activities; and  

d)  BAC Chairman and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that provisions of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and COA Circular Nos. 200-01 and 2012-01 are strictly adhered to.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:

Inventory Committee to include in the conduct of inventory of the properties of the municipality the infrastructures and other community facilities and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the LGU;


The GSO to render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period; 


